    <bioghist encodinganalog="545$a">
      <head>Historical Information 
</head>
      <p>Bland County is said to have been named for Richard Bland, a leader of colonial Virginia's resistance to Great Britain in the 1760s and 1770s.  It was formed from Giles, Wythe, and Tazewell Counties in 1861, and another part of Giles was added in 1900.  Its area is 369 square miles, and the county seat is Bland.
</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520$a">
      <head>Scope and Content
</head>
      <p>Bland County (Va.) Records, 1861-1957, includes miscellaneous records from the following series: Circuit Court Records, County Court Records, Justice of the Peace Records, Election Records, Marriage Records and Vital Statistics, Fiduciary Records, Land Records, Military and Pension Records, Tax and Fiscal Records, Clerk's Records, Board of Supervisors, and Road and Bridge Records.
</p>
    </scopecontent>
